<dl id="n03143d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03143d">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03143d"> 143(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Priests buys Is / clothes <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03143d"><li>FW 279. </li><li><a href="../../flex/le/lexle.htm#n03143d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/le/l39le.htm#n03143d">1939</a>f1 <a href="../../flex/le/lexle.htm#f101">&nbsp;fn101</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03143d">MS BL 47478-302v</ms> </li><li>JJA 52:229 <a name="led0" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#led0">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/le/led0.htm#n03143d">Draft: II.2&sect;6.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Ogrin</mark> &hellip; had travelled on his crutch to Saint Michael&apos;s Mount, and there he <mark>bought vair, squirrel fur, and ermine, silken stuffs of purple and scarlet, a shift whiter than lilies, and a palfrey caparisoned with gold</mark>, which ambled gently. Folk laughed to see him spend the coins he had laid up for so many years on these strange and sumptuous purchases; but the old man loaded the horse with the rich stuffs and <mark>returned to Iseult</mark>. &ldquo;Queen, your garments are in rags; accept these gifts, that you may be more beautiful, the day you go to the Ford Perilous &hellip;&rdquo; <small> Joseph B&eacute;dier, <a name="JBLR1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JBLR1"><cite title="source">Le roman de Tristan et Iseut</cite></a> (1900) XI &lsquo;Le Gu&eacute; Aventureux&rsquo;, 124 [The Ford Perilous, 122]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
